Interactive musical scales and chords

Last modified: 27. April 2024

Simple, compact lists of common musical scales and chord progressions. Most scales and chords shown on this page are mainly used in Western music, although some scales (such as pentatonic modes) are common all around the world.

Musical scales and modes

Common musical scales and their modes in 12 equal temperament tuning.

The scales in this section consist of a subset of pitch classes from a set of 12 equally spaced pitches, each a semitone/half-step apart (12 TET). Each scale group name is based on the amount of pitch classes in its scales, for example 5 → pentatonic, 6 → hexatonic, etc.

Each scale is laid out over a row of 12 pitch classes, where filled squares contain the scale degree of a note which is a part of the scale. Note that the position of a square indicates pitch class, which in this case is the amount of semitones/half-steps from scale degree 1.

Modes of the same scale are listed in order of distance from the 1st mode. Each mode is produced by rotating the list semitones/half-steps of the previous mode once to the left. For example, the major pentatonic scale (mode 1) consists of the steps [2, 2, 3, 2, 3]. The second mode of that, suspended pentatonic (mode 2), would be [2, 3, 2, 3, 2]. Note how all steps have moved once to the left, and the first one has jumped to the back. This approach is used for every mode listed on this page.

Common chord progressions

This section lists some common chord progressions, collected from Wikipedia and YouTube. Most chord progressions are from David Bennett's playlist of chord progressions

Note that you must be aware of which scale you are using in order to get the correct chords. For example, if the tonic is a minor chord (i) and you play a progression in C natural minor, then III, VI, and VII would be E♭, A♭, and B♭, NOT E, A, and B.

However, when the progression contains a chord which temporarily deviates from the tonic key, accidentals will be marked on numerals. For example, the chord progression C – A♭ – B♭ – G in C major is not equivalent to I – VI – VII – V due to the two lowered chords. In this case, the table below would show the progression as I – ♭VI – ♭VII – V.
